Let us now consider the ideal 2D case. For allowed transitions, the energies of bound excitons obey the dependence En = −RX/(n + 1/2)2, where n = 0, 1, 2, … and the ground-state corresponds to n = 040. As can be easily counted, the P2 scattering will produce a photon with energy 329RX\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{{32}}{9}R_{\mathrm{X}}$$\end{document}, and the bandgap will be situated at the energy 4RX, i.e., ~20 meV above EX. Forbidden transitions in the 2D case can start from n = 1 only1,40. The respective bandgap would be 4RX/9 = 28 meV above EX. We discard this possibility because the transitions in InSe are at least partly allowed.

